														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1080140">
									

<p>Honestly it'd probably be gone for good if they… say… threw it into the sun. Just smashing it or grinding it down to a powder won't work though. Plus the pieces have to be put near each other. Or maybe weirder stuff happens if they are apart for a long time and/or exposed to additional portions of jade.</p>
<p>But, obviously, there is potential for reverse-engineering the memetic shield effect - given the number of memetic hazards the Foundation has to deal with, such shielding would be very useful. Testing what it can and can't recover from when those limits are not known and when only one example is known to exist is extremely counterproductive.</p>
<p>If memory serves the "it eats other bits of jade" thing was there primarily to increase the weird factor, rather than anything <em>truly</em> sinister. Something to suggest that there was something not <em>quite</em> right about it, but not (immediately?) hazardous to mankind. Perhaps if it absorbs enough it replicates itself or evolves somehow? Maybe it only absorbs green jade? If it doesn't, does this have an impact on it's appearance and effects, or is it always the same old green ring? Something to think about for experiment logs?</p>
<p>I like to think the Foundation is looking to do more than just Contain some of this stuff though, either for their own ends - such as developing new equipment for personnel to use when containing SCPs - or public use; for example… maybe velcro and post-it notes were actually made by aliens! The history books say otherwise because that's what the Foundation want people to believe, whilst they fund themselves with the royalties from the things they do make safe and useful.</p>

							</div>

								
					
